    "Theorem 4.7.",
    "Define s, s * as in (4.28) and R 0 (s, s *) as in (2.15), and assume that b δ > δ+ν µ.",
    "If R 0 (s, s *) < 1, then there is a positive constant C (depending on the ambient parameters but independent of σ β, σ µ) such that any solution (S, I, R, S *, I *, R *) of (3.1) satisfies(4.29) lim sup t→∞ 1 t t 0 (S -s) 2 + I 2 + R 2 + (S * -s *) 2 + (I *) 2 + (R *) 2)dt ≤ C(σ 2 β + σ 2 µ)Remark 4.8.",
    "This theorem encapsulates a stochastic version of theorem 2.5(ii), and of theorem 2.5(iii) in the general case (i.e., any ξ ∈ (0, 1] and ν ≥ 0).",
    "Sending σ β, σ µ → 0 one recovers versions of theorems 2.5(ii),(iii) which are stronger in the sense that they are global results, but weaker in the mode of convergence to the equilibrium point."
